  "created": "2025-10-15",
  "description": "Nucleotide Excision Repair (NER) in E. coli removes bulky DNA lesions including UV-induced cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers (CPDs), 6-4 photoproducts, and chemical adducts. The UvrABC system performs damage recognition, dual incision, and excision of a 12-13 nucleotide oligomer containing the lesion. UvrA-UvrB complex scans DNA for helix distortions, UvrB verifies damage and remains bound, UvrA dissociates, UvrC catalyzes dual incisions (5' and 3' to lesion), UvrD helicase removes the excised fragment, DNA polymerase I fills the gap, and DNA ligase seals the nick. This flowchart illustrates the complete NER pathway from damage recognition through strand restoration, including both transcription-coupled and global genome repair sub-pathways.",
  "id": "ecoli_nucleotide_excision_repair",
